=begin
# Langtons Ant

# You must create a grid of squares
# input 
- a grid (an array of arrays) representing the current board
- the ants current column placement on the board 
- the ants current row placement
- the number of iterations of the Langton's ant
- dir, the ants current direction

Rules
- the grid will have no limit 
- if the ant enters a white square (1), it will turn 90 degrees right, flip the color, and move forward one unit
- if the ant enters a black square (0), it will turn 90 degrees left, flip the color, and move forward one unit
- if the ant moves east or west into unknown territory, the current array is expanded by 1 - east appended, west prepended
- if the ant moves north or south into unknown territory, a new array is created.
- each time the ant moves into unknown therritory, the territory created will be a black square

- White squares are represented by 1's 
- Black squares are represented by 0's 

Implicit requirements
- The O position of the ant is the north-west corner of the grid

How a turn works
# if the number of iterations is 0, return the input grid 
# get the color of the grid at the ants current position
# change direction based on the color - save the new direction
# find the color of the ants current position in the grid
# flip the color of the current position in the grid - update the grid 
# move one step in that direction - save the position 
# Check the new position against the grid
# if outside the grid, update the grid to include position
# start new turn with with n - 1 iterations

Examples
ant([[1]], 0, 0, 1, 0)   # should return: [[0, 0]]
- The ant starts at position [0, 0] which is the northwest corner. At this moment in time, there is only this grid position, and it is white (it has value 1)
- The ant has position north but this changes to east according to the rules for black/yellow grid values
- the grid then flips from [[1]] to [[0]] 
- the ant then moves 1 position east [[0, 0]] so that its row is now 0 and its column is 1.
- The grid is updated to contain the new position
- The grid is then returned 

ant([[1]], 0, 0, 3, 0) should return [[0, 1], [0, 1]]
- The ant starts at position [0, 0], this grid position is white
- The ant has position north but this changes to east according to the rules for black/yellow grid values
- the grid then flips from [[1]] to [[0]] 
- the ant then moves 1 position east [[0, 0]] so that its row is now 0 and its column is 1.
- The grid is updated to contain the new position
- The ant now starts at position [1, 0], this grid position is black
- The grid flips from black to white i.e [0, 1] 
- the ant has position east, but this changes to north according to the rules given
- the ant then moves 1 position north,this place is black
- since it is black it moves 90 degrees left, to west. it changes the grid from 0 to 1
- since this was the last iteration, the grid is returned as [[0, 1], [0, 1]]

Data structure
Create an array to hold subarrays, each array is a row, elements are column values. 

High Level Algorithm

Move forward method 
# Input: Ant direction, row and col position
# Output: returns new row and col position 

# Turn method
# Input - direction and color 
# output - direction 

# Get color method
# input: two integers (row and col) 
# returns - an integer (0 or 1)

# Flip color
# input: position
# return: grid with flipped position

# Update grid
# input: position
# return: array of arrays 

=end 

def get_color(grid, col, row)
    grid[row][col]
end 

def change_dir(color, dir) 
    case color
        when 0 then dir -= 1
        when 1 then dir += 1
    end
    case 
    when dir < 0 then dir = 3
    when dir > 3 then dir = 0
    end 
    dir 
end 

def flip_color(grid, col, row)
    flip = {1 => 0, 0 => 1}
    grid[row][col] = flip[grid[row][col]]
    grid 
end 

def move_forward(dir, col, row)
    case dir
    when 0 then row -= 1
    when 1 then col += 1
    when 2 then row += 1
    when 3 then col -= 1 
    end
    return col, row 
end 

def update_grid(grid, col, row)
    if row < 0 
        new_row = Array.new(size = grid[0].size, default = 0)
        grid.unshift(new_row)
        row = 0 
    elsif row >= grid.size 
        new_row = Array.new(size = grid[0].size, default = 0)
        grid.push(new_row)
    elsif col < 0 
        grid.each { |row| row.unshift(0) } 
        col = 0
    end 
    grid.each { |sub_array| sub_array << 0 if col >= grid[row].size }
    return grid, col, row 
end 


def ant(grid, col, row, n, dir = 0) 
    return grid if n == 0
    color = get_color(grid, col, row)
    dir = change_dir(color, dir)
    grid = flip_color(grid, col, row)
    col, row = move_forward(dir, col, row)
    grid, col, row = update_grid(grid, col, row) 
    ant(grid, col, row, n - 1, dir)
end 

p ant([[1]], 0, 0, 1, 0)
p ant([[0]], 0, 0, 1)
p ant([[1]], 0, 0, 3, 0)